The paper deals with learning strategies for games through gameplay, which is a common problem in artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG). The focus is on zero-sum stochastic games, which fall under the category of game theory (cs.GT). The proposed approach involves using a belief distribution over possible environments, which is a common technique in control systems (cs.SY) and multi-agent systems (cs.MA).
